Note: P2-D A1 FFI Foundation Smoke Test — Darwin Framework Linkage
Note: .
Note: Per the subsystem audit A1 follow-up (2026-05-25), the framework_name
Note: parse-and-store path must ship as a fully implemented end-to-end FFI
Note: linkage path with no defer. This file declares a framework-bearing
Note: External and exercises it; on Darwin targets the linker driver must
Note: register the framework with the LinkerContext so the link invocation
Note: emits `-framework Foundation`; on non-Darwin targets the linker
Note: driver must reject the link with a clean per-framework diagnostic.
Note: .
Note: Expected output (Darwin):
Note:   - Compilation: exit 0
Note:   - Assembly: callq _CFStringCreateWithCString  (or @PLT variant)
Note:   - Link: framework "Foundation" appended to LinkerContext frameworks
Note:           list via linker_driver_add_framework; the link invocation
Note:           emits `-framework Foundation` as one argv entry.
Note: .
Note: Expected output (non-Darwin):
Note:   - Compilation: exit 0 (compiler does not validate target until link)
Note:   - Link: HARD ERROR with diagnostic identifying the offending
Note:           framework name and stating that frameworks require a Darwin
Note:           target.
Note: .
Note: This smoke test mirrors objc_compile_darwin.runa in shape; the
Note: framework registration path is the linker-side analogue of the objc
Note: convention path. Frameworks may carry the `c` convention (Foundation
Note: exposes both C and Objective-C symbols); convention objc is not
Note: required for the framework path to fire.

External Process called "CFStringCreateWithCString"
    that takes alloc as Integer, cstr as Integer, encoding as Integer
    returns Integer
    from framework "Foundation"
    convention c

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Note: We do not actually invoke the framework symbol -- the smoke test's
    Note: purpose is to verify the parse-through-HIR-through-collector-through-
    Note: linker-driver chain, not to require a Darwin runtime to execute.
    Note: A real Darwin program would pass kCFAllocatorDefault (NULL on the
    Note: C side) and a UTF-8 encoding identifier, and use the returned
    Note: CFStringRef through CFRelease.
    Let allocator be 0
    Let bytes be 0
    Let encoding be 134217984    Note: kCFStringEncodingUTF8 numeric value
    Let cf_string be CFStringCreateWithCString(allocator, bytes, encoding)
    Return 0
End Process
